cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 80 miles NNW of the western tip of Cuba, lingering just north of the Yucatan Channel

motion.direction: Stationary (expected to begin moving slowly north)

cyclone.trajectory: Forecast to drift northward through the east-central Gulf, then turn northeast toward Florida’s Big Bend and move inland across north Florida and southern Georgia
cyclone.expected_landfall_location: Florida Big Bend coast (between Cedar Key and Apalachicola)

weather_observation.watch_coast: Cuban provinces of La Habana, Artemisa, Mayabeque, Pinar del Rio, and the Isle of Youth (Tropical Storm Watch)
weather_observation.impacted_coast: Florida Keys, Gulf Coast of Florida, Florida Big Bend, and eventually portions of the Georgia coast including Brunswick
weather_observation.wind: Low chance (≤5%) of sustained tropical-storm-force winds; most likely breezy with occasional gusts below gale force
weather_observation.storm_surge: No significant storm-surge threat anticipated along the Georgia coast
weather_observation.rainfall: Bands of moderate to heavy rain possible late week into Saturday as Eta or its remnants cross Georgia
weather_observation.other_hazards: Dangerous rip currents along Georgia and northeast Florida beaches late week
